e]\n\n{{Doctor Who}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of Doctor Who characters|Supporting characters]]\n[[Category:Recurring characters in Doctor Who| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of minor fictional characters|Doctor Who]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who lists|Supporting Characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Doctor Who'' supporting characters}}\nOver the course of its many years on television, the long-running British [[science fiction on television|science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]'' has not only seen changes in the actors to play [[Doctor (Doctor Who)#Changing faces|the Doctor]], but in '''the supporting cast''' as well.\n\n==Companions==\n{{main article|Companion (Doctor Who)}}\n[[Doctor (Doctor Who)|The Doctor]] is usually accompanied in his travels by one to three [[companion (Doctor Who)|companions]] (sometimes called assistants). These characters provide a [[audience surrogate|surrogate]] with whom the audience can identify, and further the story by asking questions and getting into trouble, (similar to Dr. Watson in the [[Sherlock Holmes]] mysteries.) The Doctor regularly gains new companions and loses old ones; sometimes they return home, or find new causes on worlds they have visited. A few of the companions have died during the course of the series.\n\n==Recurring characters==\n\n===UNIT personnel===\n{{Main|List of UNIT personnel}}\n*[[Brigadier Lethbridge-Stewart|Brigadier Sir Alistair Gordon Lethbridge-Stewart]] ([[Nicholas Courtney]])\n*[[Winifred Bambera|Brigadier Winifred Bambera]] ([[Angela Bruce]])\n*[[List of UNIT personnel in Doctor Who#Kate Stewart|Kate Stewart [n\u00e9e Lethbridge-Stewart]]] ([[Beverley Cressman]], [[Jemma Redgrave]])\n*[[Captain Mike Yates]] ([[Richard Franklin (actor)|Richard Franklin]])\n*[[List of UNIT personnel#Captain Erisa Magambo|Captain Erisa Magambo]] ([[Noma Dumezweni]])\n*[[Sergeant Benton|Corporal/Sergeant/Warrant Officer Benton]] ([[John Levene]], Darren Plant, [[Steven Stanley]])\n*[[List of UNIT personnel#Corporal Bell|Corporal Bell]] ([[Fernanda Marlowe]])\n*[[List of UNIT personnel#Private Carl Harris|Private Carl Harris]] ([[Clive Standen]])\n*[[List of UNIT personnel#Petronella Osgood|Petronella Osgood]] ([[Ingrid Oliver]])\n\n===Other humans===\nThis list includes characters who appear to be human and who are not known to be anything other than human, even if having originated extra-terrestrially.\n*[[Ashildr]] a/k/a [[Ashildr|Lady Me]] ([[Maisie Williams]])<ref>Ashildr/Me is a substantial supporting character in the [[Twelfth Doctor]] episodes \"[[The Girl Who Died]]\", \"[[The Woman Who Lived]]\", \"[[Face the Raven]]\", and \"[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]\"</ref>\n*[[Henry Avery|Captain Henry Avery]] ([[Hugh Bonneville]])<ref>Captain Avery is a substantial character in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episode \"[[The Curse of the Black Spot]]\", and also appears  in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episode \"[[A Good Man Goes to War]]\".</ref>\n*Toby Avery ([[Oscar Lloyd]])<ref>Toby Avery appears in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episodes \"[[The Curse of the Black Spot]]\" and the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episode \"[[A Good Man Goes to War]]\".</ref>\n*Sophie Benson ([[Daisy Haggard]])<ref>Sophie Benson is a supporting character in \"[[The Lodger (Doctor Who)|The Lodger]]\", co-stars in the mini-episode \"[[Night and the Doctor#.22Up All Night.22|Up All Night]]\", and appears again in \"[[Closing Time (Doctor Who)|Closing Time]]\" (each is an [[Eleventh Doctor]] story).</ref>\n*Captain Carter of [[List of Doctor Who robots#Teselecta|the Teselecta]] ([[Richard Dillane]])<ref>Captain Carter appears in \"[[Let's Kill Hitler]]\", and  \"[[The Wedding of River Song]]\", both being [[Eleventh Doctor]] stories.</ref>\n*Nasreen Chaudhry ([[Meera Syal]])<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n*[[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Winston Churchill]] ([[Ian McNeice]])<ref>Winston Churchill appears in \"[[Victory of the Daleks]]\" \"[[The Pandorica Opens]]\", and \"[[The Wedding of River Song]]\", each of which is an [[Eleventh Doctor]] story.</ref>\n*computer programmer, unnamed ([[Jo Stone-Fewings]])<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">This unnamed computer programmer appears in the [[Ninth Doctor]] stories \"[[Bad Wolf]]\" & \"[[The Parting of the Ways]]\".</ref>\n*[[Gwen Cooper]] ([[Eve Myles]])<ref>''[[Torchwood]]'' co-starring character Gwen Cooper appears in the [[Tenth Doctor]] episodes \"[[The Stolen Earth]]\" & \"[[Journey's End]]\". Before Gwen's creation, Eve Myles portrayed Gwen's ancestor or distant relative, Gwyneth, in the [[Ninth Doctor]] episode, \"[[The Unquiet Dead]]\"; the Tenth Doctor and [[Rose Tyler]] recognise the two women's relationship in \"[[Journey's End (Doctor Who)|Journey's End]]\".</ref>\n*\"Danny Boy\" and Captain Archibald Hamish Lethbridge-Stewart ([[Mark Gatiss]])<ref>Danny Boy appears in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episodes \"[[Victory of the Daleks]]\" and \"[[A Good Man Goes to War]]\", and Captain Lethbridge-Stewart appears in the [[Twelfth Doctor]] finale [[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon A Time]]</ref>\n*[[Special Agent]] Canton Everett Delaware III ([[W. Morgan Sheppard]], [[Mark Sheppard]])<ref>Canton Delaware appears in \"[[The Impossible Astronaut]]\", \"[[Day of the Moon]]\" and \"[[The Wedding of River Song]]\".</ref>\n*Miss Dexter ([[Elize du Toit]])<ref>Miss Dexter appears in the [[Tenth Doctor]] episodes \"[[42 (Doctor Who)|42]]\" in which she is credited simply as 'Sinister Woman', and \"[[The Sound of Drums]]\" in which her name is given in the credits.</ref>\n*[[Charles Dickens]] ([[Simon Callow]])<ref>Charles Dickens is a supporting character in the [[Ninth Doctor]] episode \"[[The Unquiet Dead]]\" and features in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episode \"[[The Wedding of River Song]]\".</ref>\n*[[Queen Elizabeth I]] ([[Vivienne Bennett]], [[Angela Pleasence]], [[Joanna Page]])<ref>Queen Elizabeth I makes appearances in the [[First Doctor]] serial ''[[The Chase (Doctor Who)|The Chase]]'', and the [[Tenth Doctor]] episode \"[[The Shakespeare Code]]\" and the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episode \"[[The Day of the Doctor]]\".</ref><ref>Queen Elizabeth I is referred to in \"[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]]\" in which the [[Tenth Doctor]] explains that he married her (the wedding was later filmed for \"The Day of the Doctor\"), \"[[The Beast Below]]\" in which her far future successor, Queen Elizabeth X chides the [[Eleventh Doctor]] about the relationship, and \"[[The Wedding of River Song]]\" in which the [[Eleventh Doctor]] notes that he could revisit her before their wedding (which he later does in \"The Day of the Doctor\"). The then-Lady Elizabeth is off-camera in \"[[The Power of Three (Doctor Who)|The Power of Three]]\" in which [[Amy Pond]] becomes the accidental wife of [[Henry VIII]], thus making Lady Elizabeth her step-daughter and the step-sister of the Doctor's other known wife, [[River Song (Doctor Who)|River Song]]. Then-Lady Elizabeth is also off-camera with her sister [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]], in ''[[Lost in Time (The Sarah Jane Adventures)|Lost in Time]]'', their approach spelling doom for the [[Pretender|Pr\u00e9tendre]] [[Lady Jane Grey|Queen Jane]].</ref>\n*[[Queen Elizabeth II]] ([[Jeannette Charles]], [[Queen Elizabeth II|Herself]] [archival], [[Jessica Martin]] [voice], [[Angharad Baxter]] [body])<ref>Queen Elizabeth II is seen in the [[Seventh Doctor]] serial ''[[Silver Nemesis]]'' (played by [[Jeanette Charles]]) and \"[[Voyage of the Damned (Doctor Who)|Voyage of the Damned]]\" ([[Jessica Martin]] providing her voice, and [[Angharad Baxter]] acting on-camera).</ref><ref>Queen Elizabeth II is also present but unseen in the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]] at the end of the [[Tenth Doctor]] episode \"[[Fear Her]]\" and in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] mini-episode \"[[Good as Gold (Doctor Who)|Good as Gold]]\", both of which take place with the torch's arrival, and thus after Her Majesty's entrance and formal opening of the games; and is at an off-camera party outside of the TARDIS in the Eleventh Doctor mini-episode, \"[[Night and the Doctor|Bad Night]]\" (the Queen is unidentified in the mini-episode itself, but is revealed as \"Liz Two\" in the associated behind-the-scenes featurette.</ref><ref>An alternate universe Queen Elizabeth II is said to have been executed prior to the events of the [[Third Doctor]] serial ''[[Inferno (Doctor Who)|Inferno]]'', and another alternate universe ER II is killed in the [[Tenth Doctor]] episode \"[[Turn Left (Doctor Who)|Turn Left]]\", in the Doctor-less version of the events of \"[[Voyage of the Damned (Doctor Who)|Voyage of the Damned]]\".</ref>\n*Queen Elizabeth X, a/k/a \"Liz 10\" ([[Sophie Okonedo]])<ref>Queen Elizabeth X appears in \"[[The Beast Below]]\" and \"[[The Pandorica Opens]]\", both of which are [[Eleventh Doctor]] episodes.</ref>\n*Elliot (Samuel Davies)<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Nia Roberts appears in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episodes \"[[The Hungry Earth]]\" & \"[[Cold Blood (Doctor Who)|Cold Blood]]\"</ref>\n*female programmer, unnamed (Nisha Nayar)<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n*[[Jenny Flint]] ([[Catrin Stewart]])<ref>Jenny Flint first appears in the Eleventh Doctor episode \"[[A Good Man Goes to War]]\", co-stars in the mini-episodes \"[[The Snowmen#Prequels|The Battle of Demon's Run - Two Days Later]]\", \"[[The Snowmen#Prequels|The Great Detective]]\", & \"[[The Snowmen#Prequels|Vastra Investigates]]\", and appears again in \"[[The Snowmen]]\", \"[[The Snowmen#Prequels|Songtaran Carols]]\", \"[[The Crimson Horror]]\", and \"[[The Name of the Doctor]]\", each of which is an [[Eleventh Doctor]] episode. She is then seen in the [[Twelfth Doctor]] episode, \"[[Deep Breath (Doctor Who)|Deep Breath]]\"</ref>\n*floor manager, unnamed ([[Jenna Russell]])<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n*Midshipman Alonzo Frame ([[Russell Tovey]])<ref>Alonzo Frame appears in the [[Tenth Doctor]] episode \"[[Voyage of the Damned (Doctor Who)|Voyage of the Damned]]\" and again briefly in \"[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]]\".</ref>\n*French newsreader, unnamed ([[Anthony Debaeck]])<ref>''[[Doctor Who]]'': [[Ninth Doctor]] episode \"[[Army of Ghosts]]\";<br>''[[Torchwood]]'': [[Torchwood: Children of Earth|''Torchwood: Children of Earth'' \"Day Three\" & \"Day Four\"]];<br>''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]'': \"[[Secrets of the Stars]]\"<br>He and [[Trinity Wells]] (below) are the only two characters to appear in all three series, although the TARDIS is ''heard'' in all three.</ref>\n*[[Paul Gachet|Dr Paul-Ferdinand Gachet]] ([[Howard Lee (actor)|Howard Lee]])<ref>Gachet is depicted in his portrait by van Gogh in \"[[Vincent and the Doctor]]\" Howard Lee makes an appearance as Gachet in eleventh Doctor story \"[[The Pandorica Opens]]\". Both are [[Eleventh Doctor]] episodes.</ref>\n*[[Vincent van Gogh]] ([[Tony Curran]])<ref>Vincent van Gogh is a major character in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episode \"[[Vincent and the Doctor]]\" and reappears briefly in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episode \"[[The Pandorica Opens]]\".</ref>\n*[[Inspector#United Kingdom|Detective Inspector]] Gregson ([[Paul Hickey]])<ref>DI Gregson is first seen in the [[Eleventh Doctor]]-era webisode, \"[[The Snowmen#Prequels|Vastra Investigates]]\". He gains his surname when he returns in the [[Twelfth Doctor]] episode, \"[[Deep Breath (Doctor Who)|Deep Breath]]\".</ref>\n* [[List of Doctor Who villains#Yvonne Hartman|Yvonne Hartman]] ([[Tracy-Ann Oberman]])<ref>Yvonne Hartman is a character in the [[Ninth Doctor]] episodes \"[[Army of Ghosts]]\" & \"[[Doomsday (Doctor Who)|Doomsday]]\".</ref>\n*Clive Jones ([[Trevor Laird]])<ref>Clive Jones appears in the [[Tenth Doctor]] episodes \"[[Smith and Jones (Doctor Who)|Smith and Jones]]\", \"[[The Sound of Drums]]\", and \"[[Last of the Time Lords]]\".</ref>\n*Francine Jones ([[Adjoa Andoh]])<ref>Francine Jones appears in the [[Tenth Doctor]] episodes \"[[Smith and Jones (Doctor Who)|Smith and Jones]]\", \"[[The Lazarus Experiment]]\", \"[[42 (Doctor Who)|42]]\", \"[[The Sound of Drums]]\", \"[[Last of the Time Lords]]\", \"[[The Stolen Earth]]\", and \"[[Journey's End (Doctor Who)|Journey's End]]\".</ref>\n*[[Harriet Jones]], former Prime Minister ([[Penelope Wilton]])<ref>Harriet Jones is introduced in the [[Ninth Doctor]] episodes \"[[Aliens of London]]\" & \"[[World War Three (Doctor Who)|World War Three]]\" and features again in the [[Tenth Doctor]] episodes \"[[The Christmas Invasion]]\" and \"[[The Stolen Earth]]\".</ref>\n*[[Ianto Jones]] ([[Gareth David-Lloyd]])<ref>''[[Torchwood]]'' co-starring character Ianto Jones appears in the [[Tenth Doctor]] episodes \"[[The Stolen Earth]]\" & \"[[Journey's End]]\".</ref>\n*Leo Jones ([[Reggie Yates]])<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Leo Jones appears in the [[Tenth Doctor]] episodes \"[[Smith and Jones (Doctor Who)|Smith and Jones]]\", \"[[The Lazarus Experiment]]\", \"[[The Sound of Drums]]\", and \"[[Last of the Time Lords]]\".</ref>\n*Letitia \"Tish\" Jones ([[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]])<ref>Tish Jones appears in the [[Tenth Doctor]] episodes \"[[Smith and Jones (Doctor Who)|Smith and Jones]]\", \"[[The Lazarus Experiment]]\", \"[[The Sound of Drums]]\", \"[[Last of the Time Lords]]\", and \"[[Turn Left (Doctor Who)|Turn Left]]\".</ref>\n*[[President of the United States|President]] [[John F. Kennedy]] (himself,<ref>Episode 1 of the [[Seventh Doctor]] serial, ''[[Remembrance of the Daleks]]'', opens with a voice-over excerpt from John F. Kennedy's [[American University speech]] of 10 June 1963 (165 days prior to the episode's 22 November 1963 setting); the episode's cliffhanger end takes place in the early evening of 22 November, at or about the moment of Kennedy's assassination.</ref><ref>Kennedy is shown passing the [[Ninth Doctor]] on Main Street in [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]' [[Dealey Plaza]] on 22 November 1963, in a doctored version of Walt Cisco's famous photograph for the ''[[Dallas Morning News]]'', in \"[[Rose (Doctor Who episode)|Rose]]\".</ref> wax sculpture)<ref>Kennedy's wax sculpture at [[Madame Tussauds]] is featured in the [[Second Doctor]]'s premi\u00e8re serial, ''[[Spearhead From Space]]''.</ref><ref>Additionally, Kennedy's assassination - which occurred on the day before ''Doctor Who'' premi\u00e8red with \"[[An Unearthly Child]]\" (which took place one or two days ''before'' the assassination, as indicated by the presence of the French Revolution book in ''[[Remembrance of the Daleks]]'') - is addressed in ''[[Silver Nemesis]]'', \"[[Dimensions in Time]]\", \"[[Rose (Doctor Who episode)|Rose]]\", \"[[The Cambridge Spy]]\", and \"[[Let's Kill Hitler]]\". His assassination by [[Lee Harvey Oswald]] occurs off-screen during the events of ''[[Remembrance of the Daleks]]'' (at or about the time of episode 1's cliff-hanger or the beginning of episode 2), and a subtle reference is made in \"[[Asylum of the Daleks]]\" in which the two brief survivors of the starship ''Alaska''\u2019s crash are named '''Harvey''' and Oswin '''Oswald'''.</ref>\n*[[Madame Kovarian]] ([[Frances Barber]])<ref>Madame Kovarian appears briefly in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episodes \"[[Day of the Moon]]\", \"[[The Curse of the Black Spot]]\", and \"[[The Rebel Flesh]]\"/\"[[The Almost People]]\", and more substantially in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] episodes \"[[A Good Man Goes to War]]\" and \"[[The Wedding of River Song]]\".</ref>\n*Tanya Lernov (Clare Jenkins)<ref name=\"Wheel\">{{cite serial | title = [[The Wheel in Space]] | series = [[Doctor Who]] | credits = Writer [[David Whitaker (screenwriter)|David Whitaker]], from a story by [[Kit Pedler]], Director Tristan de Vere Cole, Producer [[Peter Bryant]] | network = [[BBC]] | station = [[BBC One|BBC1]] | location = London | date = 27 April {{ndash}} 1 June 1968}}</ref><ref name=\"War Ten\">{{cite serial | title = [[The War Games]] | ep